    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-06-13T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-06-13T00:00:00-05:00" n="453"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d453">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.002/6–1349: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister-Counselor of Embassy in China</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Clark</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Canton</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-06-13">June 13,
                            1949</date>.<lb/>[Received June 13—3:38 p. m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Cantel 579. Following complete list Yen Hsi-shan Cabinet announced Saturday June
                    11.</p>
                <p rend="flushleft">Vice President Executive Yuan—Chu Chia-hua.<note n="15"
                        xml:id="d453fn15">Chinese Minister of Education, 1944–48.</note>
                </p>
                <p rend="flushleft">Secretary General Executive Yuan—Chia Ching-teh.<note n="16"
                        xml:id="d453fn16">Vice President of the Chinese Examination Yuan,
                        1948–49.</note>
                </p>
                <p rend="flushleft">Ministers,</p>
                <list>
                    <item>National Defense—Yen Hsi-shan concurrently;</item>
                    <item>Foreign Affairs—Hu Shih;<note n="17" xml:id="d453fn17">Chinese Ambassador
                            to the United States, 1938–42.</note>
                    </item>
                    <item>Interior—Li Han-hun;<note n="18" xml:id="d453fn18">Governor of Kwangtung,
                            1938–45.</note>
                    </item>
                    <item>Finance—Hsu Kan;</item>
                    <item>Communications—Tuan Mu-chieh;<note n="19" xml:id="d453fn19"
                            >Secretary-general of the Chinese Judicial Yuan.</note>
                    </item>
                    <item>Economic Affairs—Liu Hang-shen;<note n="20" xml:id="d453fn20">Former
                            Chinese Vice Minister of Food.</note>
                    </item>
                    <item>Education—Han Li-wu;<note n="21" xml:id="d453fn21">Chinese Vice Minister
                            of Education.</note>
                    </item>
                    <item>Justice—Chang Shih-pen;<note n="22" xml:id="d453fn22">Grand Justice of the
                            Chinese Judicial Yuan.</note>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p rend="flushleft">Commissions—</p>
                <list>
                    <item>Mongolian-Tibetan Affairs—Kuan Chi-yu;<note n="23" xml:id="d453fn23"
                            >Chinese Minister of Food.</note>
                    </item>
                    <item>Overseas Chinese Affairs—Tai Kuei-sheng;<note n="24" xml:id="d453fn24"
                            >Chinese Vice Minister of the Kuomintang Board of Overseas
                            Affairs.</note>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p rend="flushleft">Ministers without Portfolio: <list>
                        <item>Chen Li-fu,</item>
                        <item>Chang Chun<note n="25" xml:id="d453fn25">President of the Chinese
                                Executive Yuan, 1947–48; Military and Political Affairs Director for
                                Southwest China.</note> (resigned June 12)</item>
                        <item>Wu Tieh-cheng,<note n="26" xml:id="d453fn26">Vice President of the
                                Chinese Executive Yuan, 1948–49.</note>
                        </item>
                        <pb facs="0393" n="383" xml:id="pg_383"/>
                        <item>Huang Shao-ku,<note n="27" xml:id="d453fn27">Chinese Acting Minister
                                of the Kuomintang Ministry of Information.</note>
                        </item>
                        <item>Hu Yung-chang,<note n="28" xml:id="d453fn28">Chinese Minister of
                                National Defense.</note>
                        </item>
                        <item>Wang Shih-tien (Young China Party).</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>Dept pass VOANY.<note n="29" xml:id="d453fn29">Voice of America, New York.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Sent Dept Cantel 579, repeated Nanking 387, Shanghai 328.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Clark</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
